            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">What is GeM?</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar navy"></div>
            <p class="tut-p">The Government e-Marketplace (GeM) is a digital procurement portal launched by the Government of India. All central and state government departments, PSUs, autonomous bodies, defence establishments, schools, hospitals and gram panchayats are mandated to procure goods and services through GeM wherever available.</p>
            <p class="tut-p">GeM provides a transparent, competitive marketplace where registered sellers list products with standardised specifications. Government buyers can place orders directly — or participate in bidding for bulk requirements.</p>
            <div class="tut-callout info"><strong>Key fact</strong>GeM is mandatory for central government departments for all products available on the portal. State departments have their own circulars — most are now mandated too.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tut-sec" id="tut-gvo-2">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">What is Offline Procurement?</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar navy"></div>
            <p class="tut-p">Offline procurement refers to purchases made outside the GeM portal, governed by the General Financial Rules 2017 (GFR). Under Rule 144, departments can procure goods and services by obtaining quotations directly from suppliers — without using an online portal.</p>
            <p class="tut-p">This route is used when products are not available on GeM, or when the department is not yet registered/mandated on GeM. It requires a minimum of 3 quotations from different suppliers for purchases between ₹25,001 and ₹2,50,000.</p>
            <div class="tut-callout tip"><strong>When it applies</strong>Gram panchayats, aided schools, PHCs, and many autonomous bodies frequently use offline quotation procurement as their primary purchasing method.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tut-sec" id="tut-gvo-3">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">Key Differences</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar navy"></div>
            <div class="tut-cards">
              <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">🌐</div><div class="tut-card-title">GeM — Online Portal</div><div class="tut-card-desc">Purchases made through gem.gov.in. Sellers must be registered. Order placed digitally with e-invoice generation.</div></div>
              <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">📄</div><div class="tut-card-title">Offline — Paper-Based</div><div class="tut-card-desc">Purchases made via quotations on physical/email letterhead. File maintained with comparative statement for audit.</div></div>
              <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">🏷️</div><div class="tut-card-title">GeM — Price Transparency</div><div class="tut-card-desc">All listed prices are visible and competitive. No negotiation — buy at listed or bid-determined price.</div></div>
              <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">🤝</div><div class="tut-card-title">Offline — Negotiable</div><div class="tut-card-desc">Department selects the best quote. Comparative statement is mandatory. Lowest quote need not always be selected — L1 principle applies but with justification.</div></div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tut-sec" id="tut-gvo-4">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">When to Use Which</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar navy"></div>
            <p class="tut-p">Use GeM when the product is available on the portal and your department is registered. Use offline quotation procurement when the product is not on GeM, your department is not mandated to use GeM, or you need a faster/more flexible procurement option.</p>
            <div class="tut-callout warn"><strong>Important</strong>If your department is mandated on GeM and the product is available, GeM procurement is compulsory. Offline procurement for such cases may attract audit observations.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tut-sec" id="tut-gvo-5">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">How We Help</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar navy"></div>
            <p class="tut-p">Hues MyIndia is registered on GeM and operates across both procurement routes. For GeM purchases, we provide direct listing links and handle all compliance documentation. For offline procurement, we issue formal quotations on letterhead — GFR 2017 ready, with GST and HSN codes included.</p>

          <div class="tut-sec" id="gvo-faq">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar navy"></div>
            <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can I use both GeM and offline procurement for the same purchase?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">No — a single purchase should follow one route. If the item is on GeM and you are mandated to use GeM, you cannot split the purchase to go offline. However, different items in the same indent can follow different routes if some are on GeM and others are not.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Is a GeM screenshot proof enough to justify going offline?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">A screenshot showing no results or inadequate supply on GeM is the standard documentation for justifying offline procurement. Print and retain it in your purchase file with a note confirming the date and search terms used.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can a department on GeM use quotation procurement for urgent requirements?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">In genuine emergency situations, departments may proceed with offline procurement with appropriate justification. However, this must be approved by the competent authority and documented thoroughly — urgency is one of the most commonly cited but also most scrutinised justifications in audit.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Which is faster — GeM or offline?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">GeM Direct Purchase can be completed in minutes for standard products. Offline quotation procurement typically takes 3-7 working days (time to collect quotations + comparative statement + sanction + PO). For urgent needs where the product is on GeM, GeM is significantly faster.</div>
        </div>
        </div>
          </div>
            <div class="tut-cta navy">
              <div class="tut-cta-tag">Get Started</div>
              <div class="tut-cta-h">Ready to procure?</div>
              <p class="tut-cta-p">Whether GeM or offline — we handle the documentation so you don't have to.</p>
              <button class="btn btn-primary btn-lg" onclick="goPage('services')">View All Services →</button>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div><!-- /pg-tut-gem-vs-offline -->

  <!-- ═══ TUTORIAL: Q1–Q4 Category Guide ═══ -->
  <div id="pg-tut-q1q4" style="display:none">
    <div class="tut-hero indigo">
