  <!-- ═══ TUTORIAL: GFR 2017 Rule 144 ═══ -->
  <div id="pg-tut-gfr" style="display:none">
    <div class="tut-hero amber">
      <div class="wrap">
        <div class="tut-back" onclick="goPage('knowledge')">← Back to Knowledge Hub</div>
        <div class="tut-tag">GFR 2017</div>
        <h1 class="tut-h1">GFR 2017 Rule 144 —<br>Simplified for Procurement Officers</h1>
        <p class="tut-hero-p">Rule 144 of the General Financial Rules 2017 governs how government departments can make purchases without a formal tender. Here is everything you need to know — in plain language.</p>
        <div class="tut-meta">
          <span class="tut-pill">📜 7 min read</span>
          <span class="tut-pill">🏛️ For All Departments</span>
          <span class="tut-pill">📋 Offline Procurement</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="tut-body">
        <nav class="tut-toc">
          <div class="tut-toc-title">Contents</div>
          <a onclick="document.getElementById('tut-gfr-1').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">What is GFR 2017?</a>
          <a onclick="document.getElementById('tut-gfr-2').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">What Rule 144 Says</a>
          <a onclick="document.getElementById('tut-gfr-3').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">Purchase Limits</a>
          <a onclick="document.getElementById('tut-gfr-4').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">Who Can Use It?</a>
          <a onclick="document.getElementById('tut-gfr-5').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">Steps to Follow</a>
          <a onclick="document.getElementById('tut-gfr-6').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">How We Help</a>
        </nav>
        <div class="tut-content">
          <div class="tut-sec" id="tut-gfr-1">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">What is GFR 2017?</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar amber"></div>
            <p class="tut-p">The General Financial Rules 2017 (GFR 2017) is the primary rulebook governing all financial transactions by central government departments and ministries. It covers everything from budget management to procurement, advances, and asset disposal.</p>
            <p class="tut-p">For procurement purposes, the most relevant sections are Rule 144 (purchase of goods) and the associated procedures for obtaining quotations, approvals and maintaining purchase files.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="tut-sec" id="tut-gfr-2">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">What Rule 144 Says</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar amber"></div>
            <p class="tut-p">Rule 144 of GFR 2017 provides that government departments may procure goods and services without a formal advertised tender, subject to value limits and procedural requirements. Specifically, it mandates that for purchases between ₹25,001 and ₹2,50,000, a minimum of three quotations must be obtained from different suppliers before a purchase order is raised.</p>
            <div class="tut-callout warn"><strong>Key requirement</strong>The three quotations must be from genuinely different suppliers — not three quotations from the same firm or related firms. The comparative statement must show all three clearly.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tut-sec" id="tut-gfr-3">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">Purchase Value Limits</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar amber"></div>
            <div class="tut-cards">
              <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">💰</div><div class="tut-card-title">Up to ₹25,000</div><div class="tut-card-desc">Single quotation sufficient. Purchase can be made from a reliable supplier with basic documentation.</div></div>
              <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">📋</div><div class="tut-card-title">₹25,001 – ₹2,50,000</div><div class="tut-card-desc">Minimum 3 quotations required from different suppliers. Comparative statement mandatory.</div></div>
              <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">📢</div><div class="tut-card-title">Above ₹2,50,000</div><div class="tut-card-desc">Open tender / limited tender mandatory. Quotation route not applicable at this value.</div></div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tut-sec" id="tut-gfr-4">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">Who Can Use Rule 144?</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar amber"></div>
            <p class="tut-p">Rule 144 applies to all central government departments and ministries. State departments follow similar rules under their respective state financial rules, which are largely modelled on GFR 2017. It is widely used by:</p>
            <div class="tut-cards">
              <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">🏫</div><div class="tut-card-title">Government Schools</div><div class="tut-card-desc">Kendriya Vidyalayas, Navodaya Vidyalayas, state government schools and aided institutions.</div></div>
              <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">🏥</div><div class="tut-card-title">Hospitals & PHCs</div><div class="tut-card-desc">Government hospitals, Primary Health Centres and community health centres.</div></div>
              <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">🏘️</div><div class="tut-card-title">Gram Panchayats</div><div class="tut-card-desc">Village panchayats procuring equipment, furniture and supplies for local infrastructure.</div></div>
              <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">🏛️</div><div class="tut-card-title">Autonomous Bodies</div><div class="tut-card-desc">Universities, research institutions and statutory bodies receiving government grants.</div></div>
            </div>
            <div class="tut-callout info"><strong>GeM vs Rule 144</strong>If your department is on GeM and the product is available there, you must use GeM first. Rule 144 offline route applies when the product is not on GeM or your institution is not yet mandated on GeM.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tut-sec" id="tut-gfr-5">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">Steps to Follow Under Rule 144</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar amber"></div>
            <div class="tut-steps">
              <div class="tut-step"><div class="tut-step-left"><div class="tut-step-num amber">1</div><div class="tut-step-line amber"></div></div><div class="tut-step-content"><div class="tut-step-title">Identify the Requirement</div><div class="tut-step-desc">Prepare a clear specification of the product needed — brand, model, quantity, required delivery date and estimated budget.</div></div></div>
              <div class="tut-step"><div class="tut-step-left"><div class="tut-step-num amber">2</div><div class="tut-step-line amber"></div></div><div class="tut-step-content"><div class="tut-step-title">Obtain Minimum 3 Quotations</div><div class="tut-step-desc">Invite quotations from at least 3 different suppliers. Each quotation must be on the supplier's letterhead with GST details, HSN code and unit price.</div></div></div>
              <div class="tut-step"><div class="tut-step-left"><div class="tut-step-num amber">3</div><div class="tut-step-line amber"></div></div><div class="tut-step-content"><div class="tut-step-title">Prepare Comparative Statement</div><div class="tut-step-desc">List all quotations received in a comparative statement showing supplier name, quoted price, GST, delivery terms and any remarks. Select the most suitable quote.</div></div></div>
              <div class="tut-step"><div class="tut-step-left"><div class="tut-step-num amber">4</div><div class="tut-step-line amber"></div></div><div class="tut-step-content"><div class="tut-step-title">Obtain Financial Sanction</div><div class="tut-step-desc">Get approval from the competent authority as per your department's delegation of financial powers before placing the order.</div></div></div>
              <div class="tut-step"><div class="tut-step-left"><div class="tut-step-num amber">5</div></div><div class="tut-step-content"><div class="tut-step-title">Raise Purchase Order & Receive Supply</div><div class="tut-step-desc">Issue a formal purchase order to the selected supplier. Ensure supply is received with GST invoice, delivery challan and e-way bill. File all documents for audit.</div></div></div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tut-sec" id="tut-gfr-6">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">How We Help</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar amber"></div>
            <p class="tut-p">We issue formal, GFR 2017-ready quotations on company letterhead — complete with GST registration number, HSN codes, unit pricing and applicable tax rates. Our quotations are structured specifically to be used in your comparative statement without any modification.</p>

          <div class="tut-sec" id="gfr-faq">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar amber"></div>
            <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is the maximum purchase value under GFR 2017 Rule 144?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">₹2,50,000 (two lakh fifty thousand). Purchases above this value require open tender (advertised) or limited tender. Purchases between ₹25,001 and ₹2,50,000 require a minimum of 3 quotations from different suppliers.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can we get all 3 quotations from the same supplier group?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">No — quotations must be from genuinely independent suppliers. Getting 3 quotations from related entities (same owner, group companies, or obviously coordinated quotes) is a serious audit violation known as 'collusive tendering' and can attract departmental action.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Is Rule 144 different for state governments?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">State governments have their own financial rules (State Financial Rules or Treasury Code). These are generally modelled on GFR 2017 but may have different value thresholds, number of quotations required, and approval levels. Always follow your state's applicable financial rules.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Do we need to advertise for quotations under Rule 144?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">No — Rule 144 quotations do not require public advertisement. You invite quotations directly from known or identified suppliers. The 3-quotation requirement ensures competition without the formality of open tender.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What if we receive fewer than 3 quotations?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">If despite reasonable efforts you receive fewer than 3 quotations, you can proceed with documented justification — recording the names of suppliers contacted, their response (or non-response) and the reason for proceeding with fewer quotations. Senior authority approval is required.</div>
        </div>
        </div>
          </div>
            <div class="tut-cta amber">
              <div class="tut-cta-tag">Request Quotation</div>
              <div class="tut-cta-h">Need a GFR 2017 compliant quotation?</div>
              <p class="tut-cta-p">We issue formal quotations within 4 working hours — ready for your purchase file.</p>
              <button class="btn btn-primary btn-lg" onclick="goPage('offq')">📄 Request Offline Quotation</button>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div><!-- /pg-tut-gfr -->

  <!-- ═══ TUTORIAL: Bid Types ═══ -->
  <div id="pg-tut-bid-types" style="display:none">
    <div class="tut-hero navy">
      <div class="wrap">
        <div class="tut-back" onclick="goPage('knowledge')">← Back to Knowledge Hub</div>
        <div class="tut-tag">GeM Bidding</div>
        <h1 class="tut-h1">Bid Types on GeM —<br>RA, BOQ and Custom Bids Explained</h1>
        <p class="tut-hero-p">GeM offers multiple bidding formats for government procurement. Understanding the difference between Reverse Auction, BOQ bids and custom bids helps you choose the right format for your requirement.</p>
        <div class="tut-meta">
          <span class="tut-pill">🏷️ 6 min read</span>
          <span class="tut-pill">📋 For Procurement Officers</span>
          <span class="tut-pill">🏛️ GeM Portal</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="tut-body">
        <nav class="tut-toc">
          <div class="tut-toc-title">Contents</div>
          <a onclick="document.getElementById('tut-bt-1').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">Types of GeM Bids</a>
          <a onclick="document.getElementById('tut-bt-2').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">Reverse Auction (RA)</a>
          <a onclick="document.getElementById('tut-bt-3').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">BOQ Bid</a>
          <a onclick="document.getElementById('tut-bt-4').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">Custom Bid</a>
          <a onclick="document.getElementById('tut-bt-5').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">Which to Choose?</a>
          <a onclick="document.getElementById('tut-bt-6').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">How We Participate</a>
        </nav>
        <div class="tut-content">
          <div class="tut-sec" id="tut-bt-1">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">Types of GeM Bids</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar navy"></div>
            <p class="tut-p">GeM offers three main bidding formats depending on the nature and complexity of the procurement requirement. Each type has different rules for how sellers submit prices and how the buyer evaluates responses.</p>
            <div class="tut-callout info"><strong>Key distinction</strong>Direct purchase on GeM (buying a listed product without a bid) is different from bid-based procurement. Bids are used when quantities are large, products need specifications, or multiple sellers should compete.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tut-sec" id="tut-bt-2">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">Reverse Auction (RA)</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar navy"></div>
            <p class="tut-p">A Reverse Auction is a competitive bidding format where sellers progressively lower their prices during a defined auction window. The buyer sets the initial price ceiling and sellers bid downward — the lowest bid at the end of the auction wins, subject to quality compliance.</p>
            <div class="tut-cards">
              <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">⏱️</div><div class="tut-card-title">Time-Bound</div><div class="tut-card-desc">RA bids have a fixed window — typically 4–24 hours. Sellers can revise bids downward during this window.</div></div>
              <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">📉</div><div class="tut-card-title">Price Competitive</div><div class="tut-card-desc">Best for commodity products where price is the primary differentiator and multiple sellers compete.</div></div>
              <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">✅</div><div class="tut-card-title">Transparent</div><div class="tut-card-desc">All seller bids are visible in real time, ensuring full price transparency for the buying department.</div></div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tut-sec" id="tut-bt-3">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">BOQ Bid (Bill of Quantities)</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar navy"></div>
            <p class="tut-p">A BOQ (Bill of Quantities) bid is used when the buyer needs multiple different items in a single procurement. The buyer creates a list of items with quantities, and sellers quote a price for the entire BOQ or selected line items.</p>
            <p class="tut-p">BOQ bids are common in large institutional procurement — furnishing a new office, equipping a school lab, or stocking a hospital ward — where multiple products are needed together.</p>
            <div class="tut-callout tip"><strong>Best for</strong>Multi-item procurement where you need a single seller to supply everything — simplifies delivery, documentation and payment.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tut-sec" id="tut-bt-4">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">Custom Bid</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar navy"></div>
            <p class="tut-p">A Custom Bid is used for products or services not available as standard listings on GeM. The buyer describes the requirement in detail — specifications, quantity, delivery location and technical parameters — and sellers respond with their proposals and pricing.</p>
            <p class="tut-p">Custom bids offer the most flexibility but require more detailed specification preparation from the buyer. They are used for specialised equipment, IT infrastructure, vehicles and other non-standard items.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="tut-sec" id="tut-bt-5">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">Which Bid Type to Choose?</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar navy"></div>
            <div class="tut-cards">
              <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">📦</div><div class="tut-card-title">Standard Products</div><div class="tut-card-desc">Use Reverse Auction. Works best when the product is already listed on GeM and multiple sellers compete.</div></div>
              <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">📋</div><div class="tut-card-title">Multiple Items</div><div class="tut-card-desc">Use BOQ Bid. When procuring 5+ different items together from one or more sellers.</div></div>
              <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">🔧</div><div class="tut-card-title">Specialised / Unlisted</div><div class="tut-card-desc">Use Custom Bid. For items not in GeM catalogue or requiring custom specifications.</div></div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tut-sec" id="tut-bt-6">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">How We Participate in Your Bid</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar navy"></div>
            <p class="tut-p">We participate in RA, BOQ and Custom bids across Q2, Q3 and Q4 categories through our network of 15+ registered GeM partner firms. Once you submit your bid requirement, we confirm eligibility and pricing within 4 hours and respond to the bid on the portal.</p>

          <div class="tut-sec" id="bt-faq">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar navy"></div>
            <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is the minimum duration of a Reverse Auction on GeM?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">The minimum RA duration is typically 4 hours, and the maximum is 24 hours. You can set the duration when creating the RA. Longer durations generally attract more seller participation and result in lower final prices.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can I cancel a bid after sellers have responded?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">Yes — buyers can cancel bids before the order is placed, even after receiving responses. However, repeated cancellation of bids without valid reason may attract action from GeM. Always have a genuine reason and document it.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is a split bid on GeM?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">A split bid allows you to award different line items to different sellers — useful when no single seller can supply the entire BOQ. Split is done at the time of bid evaluation, not during bid creation.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Is there a minimum value for creating a bid on GeM?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">There is no formal minimum, but bids are recommended for purchases above ₹3 lakh. Below that, Direct Purchase is more efficient. Some departments set internal policies requiring bids above certain values for additional competition.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How many sellers must respond to a bid for it to be valid?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">Technically, a single valid response is sufficient to proceed. However, for Reverse Auction, a minimum of 2 participating sellers is required for the RA to be activated. If only 1 seller responds, the RA cannot be conducted and you must either re-bid or proceed at the listed price.</div>
        </div>
        </div>
          </div>
            <div class="tut-cta navy">
              <div class="tut-cta-tag">Participate Now</div>
              <div class="tut-cta-h">Have a GeM bid to fill?</div>
              <p class="tut-cta-p">Share your bid details — we'll confirm availability and respond within 4 hours.</p>
              <button class="btn btn-primary btn-lg" onclick="openBidForm()">📋 Submit Bid Requirement</button>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div><!-- /pg-tut-bid-types -->

  <!-- ═══ TUTORIAL: Common Procurement Mistakes ═══ -->
  <div id="pg-tut-mistakes" style="display:none">
    <div class="tut-hero indigo">
      <div class="wrap">
        <div class="tut-back" onclick="goPage('knowledge')">← Back to Knowledge Hub</div>
        <div class="tut-tag">Procurement Tips</div>
        <h1 class="tut-h1">Common Procurement Mistakes<br>and How to Avoid Them</h1>
        <p class="tut-hero-p">Government procurement officers often encounter the same pitfalls. Here are the most common mistakes — and how to ensure your purchase file is complete, compliant and audit-proof.</p>
        <div class="tut-meta">
          <span class="tut-pill">⚠️ 8 min read</span>
          <span class="tut-pill">🏛️ All Departments</span>
          <span class="tut-pill">✅ Audit Guidance</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="tut-body">
        <nav class="tut-toc">
          <div class="tut-toc-title">Contents</div>
          <a onclick="document.getElementById('tut-m-1').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">Vague Specifications</a>
          <a onclick="document.getElementById('tut-m-2').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">Fewer Than 3 Quotes</a>
          <a onclick="document.getElementById('tut-m-3').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">Missing Documentation</a>
          <a onclick="document.getElementById('tut-m-4').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">Wrong Category Bid</a>
          <a onclick="document.getElementById('tut-m-5').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">Skipping Written Confirmation</a>
          <a onclick="document.getElementById('tut-m-6').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">How We Help You Avoid These</a>
        </nav>
        <div class="tut-content">
          <div class="tut-sec" id="tut-m-1">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">Mistake 1 — Vague Product Specifications</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar indigo"></div>
            <p class="tut-p">The most common audit observation is a purchase file that does not specify the exact product — brand, model number, technical parameters — before the order is placed. This opens the door to substitution of inferior products after the order is approved.</p>
            <div class="tut-callout warn"><strong>How to avoid it</strong>Always specify exact brand name, model number, key technical specifications and any certifications (BIS, ISO, CE) in your purchase indent before requesting quotations.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tut-sec" id="tut-m-2">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">Mistake 2 — Obtaining Fewer Than 3 Genuine Quotations</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar indigo"></div>
            <p class="tut-p">Under GFR 2017 Rule 144, purchases between ₹25,001 and ₹2,50,000 require a minimum of 3 quotations from genuinely different suppliers. A common audit finding is that quotations were obtained from related firms, or that two of the three quotations were clearly not competitive — suggesting they were obtained to satisfy the formality rather than for genuine competition.</p>
            <div class="tut-callout warn"><strong>How to avoid it</strong>Obtain quotations from suppliers who are genuinely independent. We can help you obtain the required number of compliant quotations from our partner network.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tut-sec" id="tut-m-3">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">Mistake 3 — Incomplete Purchase File</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar indigo"></div>
            <p class="tut-p">A complete purchase file for quotation-based procurement must include: the purchase indent, all quotations received, the comparative statement, the approval of the competent authority, the purchase order, the GST invoice, the delivery challan, the e-way bill (if applicable) and the receipt / inspection note.</p>
            <div class="tut-cards">
              <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">📄</div><div class="tut-card-title">Purchase Indent</div><div class="tut-card-desc">Signed internal document describing the requirement, quantity and budget.</div></div>
              <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">📋</div><div class="tut-card-title">Comparative Statement</div><div class="tut-card-desc">All quotations side by side with selection justification.</div></div>
              <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">🧾</div><div class="tut-card-title">GST Tax Invoice</div><div class="tut-card-desc">From the selected supplier — must show GSTIN, HSN and tax breakup.</div></div>
              <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">📦</div><div class="tut-card-title">Delivery & Receipt</div><div class="tut-card-desc">Delivery challan and signed receipt / inspection note confirming goods received.</div></div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tut-sec" id="tut-m-4">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">Mistake 4 — Bidding in the Wrong GeM Category</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar indigo"></div>
            <p class="tut-p">Creating a GeM bid in the wrong category (Q1/Q2 when the product is Q3/Q4, or vice versa) either attracts no responses or attracts ineligible sellers. Understanding the Q1–Q4 classification before creating a bid saves significant time and avoids procurement failures.</p>
            <div class="tut-callout info"><strong>How to avoid it</strong>Check the product's category on GeM before creating a bid. If unsure, contact us — we'll confirm the category and our eligibility to respond before you publish the bid.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tut-sec" id="tut-m-5">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">Mistake 5 — No Written Product Confirmation Before Order</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar indigo"></div>
            <p class="tut-p">A very common post-delivery dispute is that the product supplied does not match what was ordered — either because the GeM listing name differed from the actual product, or because the supplier substituted a different model. This is particularly common in GeM procurement where catalogue listing names can be generic.</p>
            <div class="tut-callout tip"><strong>Our policy</strong>We provide written confirmation of exact product match — brand, model, specifications — before raising any invoice or placing any order. This protects your department from substitution disputes.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tut-sec" id="tut-m-6">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">How We Help You Avoid These Mistakes</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar indigo"></div>
            <p class="tut-p">Every order through Hues MyIndia comes with the right documentation, a written product confirmation before ordering, and guidance on the correct procurement route for your requirement. We ensure your purchase file is audit-ready from the first quotation to the final delivery.</p>

          <div class="tut-sec" id="mis-faq">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar indigo"></div>
            <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is the most common CAG audit observation in procurement?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">The most frequently cited audit observations are: incomplete purchase files (missing indent or sanction), procurement made without checking GeM when the item was available, L1 not selected without justification, and acceptance of goods without proper inspection and receipt note.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can an officer be held personally liable for a procurement mistake?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">Yes — under GFR 2017 and the associated accountability framework, an officer who approves a financially irregular procurement can be held personally liable for the loss to the government. This is why documentation and adherence to financial rules is critical for every procuring officer.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What should I do if I receive goods that don't match the order?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">Do not confirm receipt on GeM. Document the discrepancy in writing (photographs, written note). Immediately notify the seller and raise a grievance on the GeM portal. Do not use the goods until the matter is resolved. Contact GeM helpdesk if the seller is unresponsive.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Is a verbal confirmation from a seller sufficient before ordering?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">No — always get written confirmation (email, WhatsApp screenshot or formal letter) from the seller confirming the exact product brand, model and specifications before placing the order. Verbal confirmations are not accepted in audit and do not protect you in disputes.</div>
        </div>
        </div>
          </div>
            <div class="tut-cta indigo">
              <div class="tut-cta-tag">Get It Right</div>
              <div class="tut-cta-h">Let us handle the compliance.</div>
              <p class="tut-cta-p">Tell us your requirement — we'll ensure every document is in order.</p>
              <button class="btn btn-primary btn-lg" onclick="goPage('services')">View All Services →</button>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div><!-- /pg-tut-mistakes -->



  <!-- ═══ ARTICLE: What is GeM Portal ═══ -->
  <div id="pg-tut-what-is-gem" style="display:none">
    <div class="tut-hero navy">
      <div class="wrap">
        <div class="tut-back" onclick="goPage('knowledge')">← Back to Knowledge Hub</div>
        <div class="tut-tag">GeM Basics</div>
        <h1 class="tut-h1">What is GeM Portal?<br>A Complete Guide for Government Buyers</h1>
        <p class="tut-hero-p">The Government e-Marketplace (GeM) is India's official online procurement portal. This guide explains what it is, who can use it, and how it works — in plain language.</p>
        <div class="tut-meta"><span class="tut-pill">📘 8 min read</span><span class="tut-pill">All Departments</span><span class="tut-pill">Beginners</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="wrap"><div class="tut-body">
      <nav class="tut-toc">
        <div class="tut-toc-title">Contents</div>
        <a onclick="document.getElementById('gem-1').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">What is GeM?</a>
        <a onclick="document.getElementById('gem-2').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">Who Can Use GeM?</a>
        <a onclick="document.getElementById('gem-3').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">What Can You Buy?</a>
        <a onclick="document.getElementById('gem-4').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">How Does Ordering Work?</a>
        <a onclick="document.getElementById('gem-5').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">Is GeM Mandatory?</a>
        <a onclick="document.getElementById('gem-6').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">Common FAQs</a>
      </nav>
      <div class="tut-content">
        <div class="tut-sec" id="gem-1">
          <h2 class="tut-sec-h">What is GeM Portal?</h2>
          <div class="tut-sec-bar navy"></div>
          <p class="tut-p">The Government e-Marketplace (GeM) is a 100% government-owned national public procurement portal launched by the Ministry of Commerce and Industry on August 9, 2016. It is a dedicated online marketplace for central and state government departments, PSUs, autonomous bodies, defence establishments, local bodies, schools, hospitals and gram panchayats to procure common-use goods and services.</p>
          <p class="tut-p">GeM replaces the earlier DGS&D (Directorate General of Supplies and Disposals) rate contract system and the manual quotation-based procurement process for most standard items. It provides full transparency, competitive pricing through reverse auction and bidding, and end-to-end digital documentation.</p>
          <div class="tut-callout info"><strong>Key fact</strong>As of 2025, GeM has processed over ₹13.75 lakh crore in transactions since inception and has 2.3+ lakh registered sellers. It is the largest public procurement portal in the world by transaction volume.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="tut-sec" id="gem-2">
          <h2 class="tut-sec-h">Who Can Use GeM?</h2>
          <div class="tut-sec-bar navy"></div>
          <p class="tut-p">GeM is open to all government organisations as buyers. This includes central government ministries and departments, state government departments, central and state PSUs, autonomous bodies and statutory institutions, defence establishments, central armed police forces, railways, schools, hospitals, gram panchayats and urban local bodies.</p>
          <div class="tut-cards">
            <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">🏛️</div><div class="tut-card-title">Central Government</div><div class="tut-card-desc">All central ministries, departments and attached offices. GeM procurement is mandatory for common-use items.</div></div>
            <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">🏢</div><div class="tut-card-title">State Governments</div><div class="tut-card-desc">State departments and PSUs. Most states have issued circulars making GeM mandatory for their entities.</div></div>
            <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">🏫</div><div class="tut-card-title">Schools & Colleges</div><div class="tut-card-desc">Government schools, KVs, NVs, state-aided institutions and universities receiving government grants.</div></div>
            <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">🏥</div><div class="tut-card-title">Hospitals & PHCs</div><div class="tut-card-desc">Government hospitals, district hospitals, primary health centres and NHM facilities.</div></div>
            <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">🏘️</div><div class="tut-card-title">Gram Panchayats</div><div class="tut-card-desc">Village panchayats using government funds for local infrastructure and services.</div></div>
            <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">🛡️</div><div class="tut-card-title">Defence & CAPF</div><div class="tut-card-desc">Defence establishments and central armed police forces for common-use procurement.</div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="tut-callout tip"><strong>Registration note</strong>Buyer registration on GeM requires a government email ID and authorisation from a senior officer (typically Deputy Secretary level or above for central departments). Contact your NIC nodal officer or GeM helpdesk at 1800-419-0666 for registration assistance.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="tut-sec" id="gem-3">
          <h2 class="tut-sec-h">What Can You Buy on GeM?</h2>
          <div class="tut-sec-bar navy"></div>
          <p class="tut-p">GeM covers a very wide range of products and services — from stationery and office supplies to heavy machinery and IT infrastructure. Common categories include IT hardware and peripherals, office furniture, electrical equipment, medical devices, vehicles, cleaning services, security services, printing, and manpower outsourcing.</p>
          <p class="tut-p">If a product is listed on GeM, departments are required to procure it through the portal rather than through offline quotation. If a product you need is not listed on GeM, you may use offline procurement under GFR 2017 Rule 144.</p>
          <div class="tut-callout warn"><strong>Important</strong>Not finding a product on GeM does not automatically mean you can go offline. You must document your search on GeM before proceeding with offline procurement — this is an audit requirement.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="tut-sec" id="gem-4">
          <h2 class="tut-sec-h">How Does Ordering on GeM Work?</h2>
          <div class="tut-sec-bar navy"></div>
          <div class="tut-steps">
            <div class="tut-step"><div class="tut-step-left"><div class="tut-step-num navy">1</div><div class="tut-step-line navy"></div></div><div class="tut-step-content"><div class="tut-step-title">Search for the Product</div><div class="tut-step-desc">Log in to gem.gov.in and search for the product by name, category or HSN code. Apply filters for brand, specifications and delivery location.</div></div></div>
            <div class="tut-step"><div class="tut-step-left"><div class="tut-step-num navy">2</div><div class="tut-step-line navy"></div></div><div class="tut-step-content"><div class="tut-step-title">Direct Purchase or Bid</div><div class="tut-step-desc">For smaller quantities or lower values, use Direct Purchase (L1 — buy from the lowest listed price). For larger requirements, create a Bid or Reverse Auction to get competitive pricing.</div></div></div>
            <div class="tut-step"><div class="tut-step-left"><div class="tut-step-num navy">3</div><div class="tut-step-line navy"></div></div><div class="tut-step-content"><div class="tut-step-title">Raise Purchase Order</div><div class="tut-step-desc">Once you select the seller, raise a formal Purchase Order on GeM. The seller is notified and confirms acceptance.</div></div></div>
            <div class="tut-step"><div class="tut-step-left"><div class="tut-step-num navy">4</div><div class="tut-step-line navy"></div></div><div class="tut-step-content"><div class="tut-step-title">Receive Supply & Confirm Delivery</div><div class="tut-step-desc">The seller dispatches the goods with invoice, e-way bill and delivery challan. You confirm receipt on the portal — this triggers the payment process.</div></div></div>
            <div class="tut-step"><div class="tut-step-left"><div class="tut-step-num navy">5</div></div><div class="tut-step-content"><div class="tut-step-title">Payment via PFMS</div><div class="tut-step-desc">Payment is processed through PFMS (Public Financial Management System) directly to the seller's bank account. No physical cheque or manual payment required.</div></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tut-sec" id="gem-5">
          <h2 class="tut-sec-h">Is GeM Mandatory?</h2>
          <div class="tut-sec-bar navy"></div>
          <p class="tut-p">Yes — for central government departments, procurement of all common-use goods and services available on GeM is mandatory under GFR Rule 149. The Ministry of Finance has issued multiple circulars reinforcing this mandate. State governments have their own circulars — most major states (including UP, Maharashtra, Karnataka, Rajasthan and others) have now mandated GeM for their departments.</p>
          <div class="tut-callout warn"><strong>Audit risk</strong>Bypassing GeM for items that are available on the portal — without proper documentation — is a serious audit observation. CAG has flagged several departments for non-compliance. Always check GeM first and document your search.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="tut-sec" id="gem-6">
          <h2 class="tut-sec-h">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
          <div class="tut-sec-bar navy"></div>
          <div class="tut-callout info"><strong>Can private companies buy on GeM?</strong>No. GeM is exclusively for government organisations and bodies funded by the government. Private companies cannot register as buyers — they can only register as sellers.</div>
          <div class="tut-callout info"><strong>Is there a minimum order value on GeM?</strong>No minimum order value. However, for purchases above ₹3 lakh, you must use a Bid or Reverse Auction instead of direct purchase at L1 price.</div>
          <div class="tut-callout info"><strong>What happens if a product is not available on GeM?</strong>You may proceed with offline procurement under GFR 2017 Rule 144. Document your GeM search result (showing no results or inadequate supply) in your purchase file before proceeding.</div>
          <div class="tut-callout info"><strong>Can I negotiate price with a GeM seller?</strong>No direct negotiation. Prices are fixed by sellers and compete through market forces. For large requirements, use Reverse Auction — prices drop automatically as sellers compete.</div>

          <div class="tut-sec" id="gem-faq">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar navy"></div>
            <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Is GeM free to use for government buyers?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">Yes — GeM is completely free for government buyers. There are no registration fees, subscription charges or transaction fees for buyer organisations. Sellers pay a small transaction fee.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can I buy from GeM without a bid?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">Yes — for purchases up to ₹3 lakh, you can use Direct Purchase (L1 price) without creating a bid. Above ₹3 lakh, you must use a Bid or Reverse Auction.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is the GeM helpdesk number?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">GeM's national helpdesk is 1800-419-0666 (toll-free). You can also raise a support ticket at gem.gov.in or email at <a href="/cdn-cgi/l/email-protection" class="__cf_email__" data-cfemail="99f1fcf5e9fdfceaf2b4fefcf4d9fefcf4b7fef6efb7f0f7">[email&#160;protected]</a>.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can I return a product bought on GeM?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">Yes — GeM has a return and replacement policy. You can raise a return request within the timeline specified in the Purchase Order (typically 10 days of delivery) if the product is defective, damaged or does not match specifications.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Is GST applicable on GeM purchases?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">Yes — GST applies to all GeM purchases as per the standard GST rate for the product category. The seller provides a GST-compliant tax invoice for every order.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What happens if a GeM seller delivers a wrong product?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">Raise a grievance on the GeM portal immediately. Do not confirm receipt of goods until the issue is resolved. GeM has a dispute resolution mechanism and can direct the seller to replace the product or refund the amount.</div>
        </div>
        </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tut-cta navy"><div class="tut-cta-tag">Need Help?</div><div class="tut-cta-h">We handle GeM for you.</div><p class="tut-cta-p">Share your product requirement — we check GeM availability and send a direct purchase link within 2 hours.</p><button class="btn btn-primary btn-lg" onclick="openReq()">🔍 Request a Product</button></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div></div>
  </div><!-- /pg-tut-what-is-gem -->

