  <!-- ═══ ARTICLE: GeM Payment Process ═══ -->
  <div id="pg-tut-payment" style="display:none">
    <div class="tut-hero navy">
      <div class="wrap">
        <div class="tut-back" onclick="goPage('knowledge')">← Back to Knowledge Hub</div>
        <div class="tut-tag">GeM Basics</div>
        <h1 class="tut-h1">GeM Payment Process —<br>From Order to PFMS Credit</h1>
        <p class="tut-hero-p">Understanding how payments work on GeM helps avoid delays and disputes. Here is the complete payment flow — from order confirmation to PFMS credit in the seller's account.</p>
        <div class="tut-meta"><span class="tut-pill">💳 6 min read</span><span class="tut-pill">Buyer &amp; Seller</span><span class="tut-pill">PFMS</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="wrap"><div class="tut-body">
      <nav class="tut-toc">
        <div class="tut-toc-title">Contents</div>
        <a onclick="document.getElementById('pay-1').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">How GeM Payments Work</a>
        <a onclick="document.getElementById('pay-2').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">PFMS Integration</a>
        <a onclick="document.getElementById('pay-3').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">Payment Timeline</a>
        <a onclick="document.getElementById('pay-4').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">Common Payment Issues</a>
      </nav>
      <div class="tut-content">
        <div class="tut-sec" id="pay-1">
          <h2 class="tut-sec-h">How GeM Payments Work</h2>
          <div class="tut-sec-bar navy"></div>
          <p class="tut-p">GeM payments are fully digital and integrated with the government's financial management systems. There is no physical cheque or manual payment — everything flows through the PFMS (Public Financial Management System) directly to the seller's registered bank account.</p>
          <p class="tut-p">The payment process is triggered automatically when the buyer confirms receipt of goods on the GeM portal. The seller does not need to submit a separate invoice to accounts — the GeM system handles end-to-end processing.</p>
          <div class="tut-callout info"><strong>Key benefit</strong>GeM's integrated payment system eliminates the traditional accounts payable process — no separate bills, no cheque requests, no delayed payment cycles. Payment is processed digitally within defined timelines.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="tut-sec" id="pay-2">
          <h2 class="tut-sec-h">PFMS Integration</h2>
          <div class="tut-sec-bar navy"></div>
          <p class="tut-p">PFMS (Public Financial Management System) is the central government's electronic payment platform, operated by the Controller General of Accounts (CGA). All central government payments — including GeM purchases — are routed through PFMS. State government departments use IFMS (Integrated Financial Management System) or equivalent state treasury systems.</p>
          <div class="tut-callout tip"><strong>For buyer departments</strong>Ensure your PFMS mapping is correctly set up before placing GeM orders. Your Drawing and Disbursing Officer (DDO) code and budget head must be correctly mapped to your GeM buyer account. Contact your PAO or Treasury office if there are PFMS integration issues.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="tut-sec" id="pay-3">
          <h2 class="tut-sec-h">Payment Timeline</h2>
          <div class="tut-sec-bar navy"></div>
          <div class="tut-steps">
            <div class="tut-step"><div class="tut-step-left"><div class="tut-step-num navy">1</div><div class="tut-step-line navy"></div></div><div class="tut-step-content"><div class="tut-step-title">Buyer Confirms Receipt</div><div class="tut-step-desc">You confirm receipt of goods on GeM portal after physical inspection. Deadline: within 10 days of delivery for most categories.</div></div></div>
            <div class="tut-step"><div class="tut-step-left"><div class="tut-step-num navy">2</div><div class="tut-step-line navy"></div></div><div class="tut-step-content"><div class="tut-step-title">Payment Order Generated</div><div class="tut-step-desc">GeM system generates a payment order and sends it to your PAO / DDO for processing through PFMS. This is automatic — no manual action required from the buyer.</div></div></div>
            <div class="tut-step"><div class="tut-step-left"><div class="tut-step-num navy">3</div><div class="tut-step-line navy"></div></div><div class="tut-step-content"><div class="tut-step-title">PAO Processes Payment</div><div class="tut-step-desc">Your Pay & Accounts Office verifies and processes the payment through PFMS. Standard processing time: 10 working days from receipt confirmation.</div></div></div>
            <div class="tut-step"><div class="tut-step-left"><div class="tut-step-num navy">4</div></div><div class="tut-step-content"><div class="tut-step-title">Credit to Seller Account</div><div class="tut-step-desc">Payment credited directly to the seller's bank account via NEFT/RTGS. Seller receives confirmation on GeM dashboard.</div></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="tut-callout warn"><strong>10-day rule</strong>Buyers must confirm receipt within 10 days of the delivery date. Failure to do so triggers an auto-confirmation — which may cause payment even if goods have not been received. Always verify before the deadline.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="tut-sec" id="pay-4">
          <h2 class="tut-sec-h">Common Payment Issues and Solutions</h2>
          <div class="tut-sec-bar navy"></div>
          <div class="tut-callout warn"><strong>Payment stuck after receipt confirmation</strong>Usually a PFMS mapping issue. Contact your PAO with the GeM order number. Ensure the budget head, DDO code and sanction number are correctly entered.</div>
          <div class="tut-callout warn"><strong>Wrong bank account credited</strong>Seller's bank account must be updated on GeM profile before order placement. Contact GeM helpdesk (1800-419-0666) if bank details need to be corrected after an order.</div>
          <div class="tut-callout warn"><strong>Buyer hasn't confirmed receipt</strong>If the buyer is not confirming receipt, the seller can raise a complaint on GeM after 10 days. GeM mediates and can trigger auto-confirmation in some cases.</div>

          <div class="tut-sec" id="pay-faq">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar navy"></div>
            <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is the payment timeline for GeM orders?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">The standard payment timeline is 10 working days from the date of receipt confirmation by the buyer. Some departments process faster; delays are usually due to PFMS mapping issues or missing budget allocation.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can a GeM seller request advance payment?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">No — GeM does not support advance payments. Payment is only processed after the buyer confirms receipt of goods. Any demand for advance payment from a seller outside GeM is a red flag.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What if a buyer does not confirm receipt within 10 days?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">GeM has an auto-confirmation mechanism — if the buyer does not confirm or raise a complaint within 10 days of the delivery date, the system may auto-confirm receipt and trigger payment. Buyers should always act within the 10-day window.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Is TDS deducted on GeM payments?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">Yes — TDS (Tax Deducted at Source) is deducted as per the Income Tax Act on payments above the threshold. The seller's PAN must be correctly registered on GeM for TDS computation. The TDS certificate is issued through Form 16A.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can a state government department use PFMS for GeM payment?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">State departments typically use IFMS (Integrated Financial Management System) or their state treasury system rather than the central PFMS. GeM has integration with most state treasury systems. Contact your state GeM nodal officer or treasury for the correct payment mapping.</div>
        </div>
        </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tut-cta navy"><div class="tut-cta-tag">No Payment Hassles</div><div class="tut-cta-h">We handle everything up to delivery.</div><p class="tut-cta-p">We supply with correct documentation so your PAO can process payment without delays or queries.</p><button class="btn btn-primary btn-lg" onclick="goPage('services')">View Our Services →</button></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div></div>
  </div><!-- /pg-tut-payment -->

  <!-- ═══ ARTICLE: Can Gram Panchayats Use GeM ═══ -->
  <div id="pg-tut-gram-panchayat" style="display:none">
    <div class="tut-hero amber">
      <div class="wrap">
        <div class="tut-back" onclick="goPage('knowledge')">← Back to Knowledge Hub</div>
        <div class="tut-tag">GeM for Institutions</div>
        <h1 class="tut-h1">Can Gram Panchayats Use GeM?<br>A Complete Guide</h1>
        <p class="tut-hero-p">Gram panchayats are eligible for GeM procurement and can also use offline quotation procurement under GFR-equivalent state rules. Here is everything you need to know.</p>
        <div class="tut-meta"><span class="tut-pill">🏘️ 6 min read</span><span class="tut-pill">Gram Panchayats</span><span class="tut-pill">Rural Procurement</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="wrap"><div class="tut-body">
      <nav class="tut-toc">
        <div class="tut-toc-title">Contents</div>
        <a onclick="document.getElementById('gp-1').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">Are GPs Eligible?</a>
        <a onclick="document.getElementById('gp-2').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">What GPs Buy on GeM</a>
        <a onclick="document.getElementById('gp-3').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">GeM vs Quotation for GPs</a>
        <a onclick="document.getElementById('gp-4').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">Registration Process</a>
        <a onclick="document.getElementById('gp-5').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">14th FC and MGNREGS Funds</a>
      </nav>
      <div class="tut-content">
        <div class="tut-sec" id="gp-1">
          <h2 class="tut-sec-h">Are Gram Panchayats Eligible for GeM?</h2>
          <div class="tut-sec-bar amber"></div>
          <p class="tut-p">Yes — gram panchayats are explicitly included in GeM's buyer eligibility. As local bodies receiving government funds (14th/15th Finance Commission grants, MGNREGS funds, state grants), gram panchayats can register on GeM and procure goods and services through the portal.</p>
          <p class="tut-p">Several state governments — including Uttar Pradesh, Rajasthan, Maharashtra and Madhya Pradesh — have issued specific directives encouraging or mandating gram panchayats to use GeM for procurement above certain value thresholds using government grant funds.</p>
          <div class="tut-callout info"><strong>Registration requirement</strong>Registration is done by the Gram Panchayat Development Officer (GPDO) or Panchayat Secretary with a government email ID. The Panchayat Raj Department of your state can provide the GeM buyer code and registration support.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="tut-sec" id="gp-2">
          <h2 class="tut-sec-h">What Do Gram Panchayats Buy on GeM?</h2>
          <div class="tut-sec-bar amber"></div>
          <div class="tut-cards">
            <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">💡</div><div class="tut-card-title">Street Lighting</div><div class="tut-card-desc">LED streetlights, solar streetlights, poles and electrical fittings for village roads and public spaces.</div></div>
            <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">🚰</div><div class="tut-card-title">Water & Sanitation</div><div class="tut-card-desc">Water storage tanks, pumps, pipes, taps and sanitation equipment for Jal Jeevan Mission and Swachh Bharat schemes.</div></div>
            <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">🏗️</div><div class="tut-card-title">Construction Materials</div><div class="tut-card-desc">Cement, steel, bricks and construction consumables for panchayat infrastructure projects.</div></div>
            <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">🖥️</div><div class="tut-card-title">Office Equipment</div><div class="tut-card-desc">Computers, printers, furniture and stationery for gram panchayat offices and CSC centres.</div></div>
            <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">🧹</div><div class="tut-card-title">Sanitation Supplies</div><div class="tut-card-desc">Cleaning equipment, dustbins, brooms and sanitation materials for village cleanliness drives.</div></div>
            <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">🌱</div><div class="tut-card-title">Horticulture & Parks</div><div class="tut-card-desc">Plants, gardening tools and park equipment for village beautification and green cover programmes.</div></div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tut-sec" id="gp-3">
          <h2 class="tut-sec-h">GeM vs Quotation-Based Procurement for Gram Panchayats</h2>
          <div class="tut-sec-bar amber"></div>
          <p class="tut-p">Gram panchayats that are not yet registered on GeM, or need to procure items not available on GeM, can use quotation-based procurement under state financial rules (equivalent to GFR 2017 Rule 144 for central bodies). This requires obtaining minimum 3 quotations from different suppliers before placing a purchase order.</p>
          <div class="tut-callout tip"><strong>Practical reality</strong>Many gram panchayats in remote areas still rely on offline procurement due to internet connectivity challenges and the complexity of GeM registration. Offline quotation procurement is a valid and legally compliant alternative for such panchayats.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="tut-sec" id="gp-4">
          <h2 class="tut-sec-h">GeM Registration Process for Gram Panchayats</h2>
          <div class="tut-sec-bar amber"></div>
          <div class="tut-steps">
            <div class="tut-step"><div class="tut-step-left"><div class="tut-step-num amber">1</div><div class="tut-step-line amber"></div></div><div class="tut-step-content"><div class="tut-step-title">Obtain Government Email ID</div><div class="tut-step-desc">Contact your Block Development Office or District Panchayat Raj Office for an official government email ID (e.g., NIC email). This is required for GeM registration.</div></div></div>
            <div class="tut-step"><div class="tut-step-left"><div class="tut-step-num amber">2</div><div class="tut-step-line amber"></div></div><div class="tut-step-content"><div class="tut-step-title">Register as Buyer on GeM</div><div class="tut-step-desc">Go to gem.gov.in, click Buyer Registration. Enter organisation details, Aadhaar of the authorised officer, and government email. Verify via OTP.</div></div></div>
            <div class="tut-step"><div class="tut-step-left"><div class="tut-step-num amber">3</div><div class="tut-step-line amber"></div></div><div class="tut-step-content"><div class="tut-step-title">Approval from Senior Officer</div><div class="tut-step-desc">Registration requires approval from a senior officer (BDO or District Level). Submit the online request and await approval — usually within 3-5 working days.</div></div></div>
            <div class="tut-step"><div class="tut-step-left"><div class="tut-step-num amber">4</div></div><div class="tut-step-content"><div class="tut-step-title">Map PFMS / Treasury Account</div><div class="tut-step-desc">Map your panchayat's fund account (PFMS, state treasury or bank account) to the GeM buyer profile for payment processing. Contact your District Treasury for assistance.</div></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tut-sec" id="gp-5">
          <h2 class="tut-sec-h">Using 14th/15th FC and MGNREGS Funds on GeM</h2>
          <div class="tut-sec-bar amber"></div>
          <p class="tut-p">Gram panchayats receiving Finance Commission grants (14th FC / 15th FC tied and untied funds) and MGNREGS material components can use these funds for GeM procurement, subject to the activity norms defined for each scheme. Ensure the product category is eligible under the scheme before placing a GeM order.</p>
          <div class="tut-callout warn"><strong>Scheme norms apply</strong>MGNREGS has specific rules on material-to-labour ratio. Ensure any GeM procurement from MGNREGS funds does not breach the 40% material limit for unskilled labour schemes. Consult your Block Programme Officer before ordering.</div>

          <div class="tut-sec" id="gp-faq">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar amber"></div>
            <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Is GeM mandatory for gram panchayats?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">It depends on your state. Several state governments have issued directives encouraging or mandating GeM for panchayat procurement above certain values. Check your state Panchayat Raj Department's latest circular. Where not mandated, quotation-based procurement under state financial rules is valid.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can a gram panchayat use 15th FC funds to buy on GeM?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">Yes — the 15th Finance Commission grants (both tied and untied) can be used for GeM procurement, subject to the eligibility norms for each fund component. Tied grants for specific activities like water and sanitation are used for those categories on GeM.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is the threshold for GeM procurement vs quotation for panchayats?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">Thresholds vary by state. Under central GFR-equivalent rules, quotation procurement is valid up to ₹2,50,000. Above that, open tender or GeM is required. Your state's Panchayat Raj financial rules will specify the applicable thresholds.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can a gram panchayat reject a GeM delivery?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">Yes — if goods delivered do not match specifications or are defective, the gram panchayat receiving officer should not sign the delivery challan and must raise the issue with the Block Development Officer and file a complaint on GeM.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How does a gram panchayat handle MGNREGS material procurement on GeM?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">MGNREGS material components (up to 40% of total wage+material cost) can be procured through GeM. The specific items allowed depend on the approved works. Procurement must be approved by the Programme Officer and mapped to the correct MIS entry in the MGNREGS Management Information System.</div>
        </div>
        </div>
