  <!-- ═══ ARTICLE: L1 Price Explained ═══ -->
  <div id="pg-tut-l1-price" style="display:none">
    <div class="tut-hero indigo">
      <div class="wrap">
        <div class="tut-back" onclick="goPage('knowledge')">← Back to Knowledge Hub</div>
        <div class="tut-tag">GeM Basics</div>
        <h1 class="tut-h1">L1 Price on GeM —<br>What It Is and How It Works</h1>
        <p class="tut-hero-p">L1 is the cornerstone of fair pricing on GeM. Understanding how L1 is determined, when you must select it, and when you can deviate — is essential for every procurement officer.</p>
        <div class="tut-meta"><span class="tut-pill">🏷️ 5 min read</span><span class="tut-pill">All Buyers</span><span class="tut-pill">Pricing</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="wrap"><div class="tut-body">
      <nav class="tut-toc">
        <div class="tut-toc-title">Contents</div>
        <a onclick="document.getElementById('l1-1').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">What is L1?</a>
        <a onclick="document.getElementById('l1-2').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">When Must You Select L1?</a>
        <a onclick="document.getElementById('l1-3').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">When Can You Deviate?</a>
        <a onclick="document.getElementById('l1-4').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">L1 in Reverse Auction</a>
        <a onclick="document.getElementById('l1-5').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'})">Make in India Preference</a>
      </nav>
      <div class="tut-content">
        <div class="tut-sec" id="l1-1">
          <h2 class="tut-sec-h">What is L1 Price?</h2>
          <div class="tut-sec-bar indigo"></div>
          <p class="tut-p">L1 (Lowest 1) refers to the lowest price listed for a product on GeM among all eligible sellers at any given time. The GeM portal automatically identifies and displays the L1 price. When you search for a product on GeM, sellers are ranked by price — L1 is the cheapest available option from a seller who can deliver to your location.</p>
          <p class="tut-p">L1 pricing ensures government departments get the most competitive price available on the market without manual negotiation, and creates a transparent, audit-proof selection process.</p>
          <div class="tut-callout info"><strong>Dynamic pricing</strong>L1 is not static. Sellers update prices in real time. The L1 at 10am may differ from L1 at 3pm. Always confirm the L1 price at the moment of raising the Purchase Order — not the price you saw earlier during your search.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="tut-sec" id="l1-2">
          <h2 class="tut-sec-h">When Must You Select L1?</h2>
          <div class="tut-sec-bar indigo"></div>
          <div class="tut-cards">
            <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">💰</div><div class="tut-card-title">₹25,001 – ₹3 Lakh</div><div class="tut-card-desc">Mandatory L1 selection. Must buy from the cheapest listed seller who can fulfil your order. GeM shows L1 prominently and asks you to confirm selection.</div></div>
            <div class="tut-card"><div class="tut-card-icon">🏷️</div><div class="tut-card-title">Above ₹3 Lakh</div><div class="tut-card-desc">Bid or Reverse Auction required. In RA, the seller who quotes lowest at end of auction becomes the new L1 — and you must accept that bid subject to quality compliance.</div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="tut-callout tip"><strong>Below ₹25,000</strong>For purchases up to ₹25,000, you may select any listed seller — not necessarily L1. You can choose based on brand, delivery time, warranty or other factors. Document your justification.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="tut-sec" id="l1-3">
          <h2 class="tut-sec-h">When Can You Deviate from L1?</h2>
          <div class="tut-sec-bar indigo"></div>
          <p class="tut-p">Deviating from L1 is allowed only in specific, documented circumstances. These include: the L1 seller cannot deliver to your location (remote/difficult area), the L1 product specifications do not match your requirement (even if the name is similar), the L1 seller is on GeM's blacklist or has unacceptably poor ratings, or fewer than 3 sellers are available and you are selecting from a limited set.</p>
          <div class="tut-callout warn"><strong>Always document</strong>Any deviation from L1 must be documented in the purchase file with clear justification. An undocumented deviation from L1 is a serious audit finding. Contact the L1 seller in writing first and retain their response.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="tut-sec" id="l1-4">
          <h2 class="tut-sec-h">L1 in Reverse Auction (RA)</h2>
          <div class="tut-sec-bar indigo"></div>
          <p class="tut-p">In a Reverse Auction on GeM, the concept of L1 is dynamic throughout the auction window. Sellers bid downward — each seller can reduce their price during the auction period. At the end of the auction window, the seller with the lowest final bid is the L1, and you must place the order with them (subject to quality checks and delivery capability).</p>
          <div class="tut-callout info"><strong>RA advantage</strong>Reverse Auction consistently delivers prices 15–30% below the listed catalogue price — because sellers compete actively. For any procurement above ₹3 lakh of standard goods, RA is almost always better value than direct purchase at L1 catalogue price.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="tut-sec" id="l1-5">
          <h2 class="tut-sec-h">Make in India Preference and L1</h2>
          <div class="tut-sec-bar indigo"></div>
          <p class="tut-p">GeM applies Make in India preferences through the Public Procurement (Preference to Make in India) Order. Products manufactured in India with local content above defined thresholds may receive a price preference of up to 20% — meaning a domestic product priced up to 20% higher than an imported alternative can still be selected as the preferred L1.</p>
          <p class="tut-p">This preference is automatically applied by the GeM portal when filtering. Ensure the "Make in India" filter is applied appropriately for your procurement — especially for products where domestic alternatives are available.</p>

          <div class="tut-sec" id="l1-faq">
            <h2 class="tut-sec-h">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
            <div class="tut-sec-bar indigo"></div>
            <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can I select L2 if L1 is slightly more expensive?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">No — you cannot select L2 simply because L1 is slightly more expensive. If both sellers offer the same product, L1 must be selected. L2 is only permissible if L1 cannot fulfil the order (delivery location issue, stock shortage, specification mismatch) — with documented justification.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Does L1 price include GST and delivery charges?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">The price displayed on GeM typically excludes GST. Delivery charges may be included or shown separately depending on the seller's listing. Always check the final cart total (inclusive of GST and delivery) before raising the Purchase Order.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What happens if L1 price changes between search and PO?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">If the L1 price increases between your search and the time you raise the PO, you must either accept the new price (if within your sanctioned budget) or seek fresh financial sanction. Document the price at time of search and at time of PO in your file.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Is there any price preference for MSME sellers on GeM?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">Yes — MSME sellers may receive a purchase preference in certain categories. GeM allows buyers to apply MSME filters. In some categories, MSME sellers with slightly higher prices may still be selected over non-MSME L1 sellers under the MSME preference policy.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How is L1 determined in a Reverse Auction?<div class="faq-icon">+</div></div>
          <div class="faq-a">In a Reverse Auction, sellers bid downward during the auction window. The seller with the lowest final bid at the close of the auction window is the new L1. You must place the order with this L1 seller, provided they accept the order and can fulfil delivery requirements.</div>
        </div>
        </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tut-cta indigo"><div class="tut-cta-tag">Always GeM Compliant</div><div class="tut-cta-h">We supply at competitive prices on GeM.</div><p class="tut-cta-p">Our products are GeM-listed at fair market prices. Tell us your requirement and we will share the direct purchase link.</p><button class="btn btn-primary btn-lg" onclick="goPage('products')">Browse Our Products →</button></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div></div>
  </div><!-- /pg-tut-l1-price -->


